r ignored. These zones are significant, contested spaces for state policy and market behaviour to interact with respect to trade, the environment, food security, and investment. Powerful incentives exist in the global economy for states to harmonize their policies through trade and investment agreements. But grey zones both promote uniformity in many areas of public life and facilitate diverse forms of capitalism in market societies. They enable governments to balance national and global economic benefits as they advance their core interests. At a time of growing nationalist sentiment, Grey Zones in International Economic Law and Global Governance explores creative local engagement with international economic law and offers a bold new way to understand public concerns about international trade and investment, food security, green energy, subsidies, and anti-dumping actions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aForeign trade regulation. 0aGray marketxLaw and legislation. 0aHuman rights. 0aIndustrial relations. 0aInternational economic relations. 0aLaw and economic development. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh1 aBarral, Welber, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiukovic, Ljiljana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroude, Tomer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrea, Carlos M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCottier, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrache, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrache, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJacobs, Lesley A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Lesley A., eeditor.4edt4htt